[
    {
        "content": "<p>Suppose you have a type with an existing LE on it - Subtype p when there's an ambient relation is a good example - and you want to assert as a hypothesis \"SemilatticeInf (Subtype p)\" - but you want the LE for that to be the one that already exists, to avoid diamond issues. How do you specify that?</p>",
        "id": 528647740,
        "sender_full_name": "Wrenna Robson",
        "timestamp": 1752495198
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess in general my question is like, why do the classes for orders mix data and propositions in this way.</p>",
        "id": 528647849,
        "sender_full_name": "Wrenna Robson",
        "timestamp": 1752495225
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Just don't</p>",
        "id": 528650075,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1752495879
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>How about <code>∀ a b, ∃ c, IsGLB {a, b} c</code></p>",
        "id": 528650223,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1752495916
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, sure, if that's a preferred spelling</p>",
        "id": 528650290,
        "sender_full_name": "Wrenna Robson",
        "timestamp": 1752495936
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I haven't seen it used anywhere</p>",
        "id": 528650399,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1752495966
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess what I don't quite get, design-wise, is why OrderBot instead has [LE _] as a required instance</p>",
        "id": 528650524,
        "sender_full_name": "Wrenna Robson",
        "timestamp": 1752496005
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>but it seems better than putting an unrelated <code>SemilatticeInf</code> on you type and then asserting a compatibility</p>",
        "id": 528650577,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1752496018
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>While SemilatticeInf doesn't do that.</p>",
        "id": 528650586,
        "sender_full_name": "Wrenna Robson",
        "timestamp": 1752496022
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It seems inconsistent to me but I feel like it's more likely I'm missing something subtlety.</p>",
        "id": 528650682,
        "sender_full_name": "Wrenna Robson",
        "timestamp": 1752496047
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"387244\">@Yaël Dillies</span> I assume you'll know why it's designed like this.</p>",
        "id": 528651495,
        "sender_full_name": "Wrenna Robson",
        "timestamp": 1752496311
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"330967\">Wrenna Robson</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/SemilatticeInf.20as.20a.20hypothesis/near/528647740\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>How do you specify that?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>You use <code>SubsemilatticeSup</code>, the missing <code>SemilatticeSup</code> counterpart to <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=Sublattice#doc\">docs#Sublattice</a></p>",
